'''William "Will" Scott Middlebrooks''' (born September 9, 1988) is an [[United States|American]] professional [[baseball]] [[third baseman]] for the [[Boston Red Sox]] of [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB). Middlebrooks made his MLB debut with the Red Sox on May 2, 2012.

A fifth round draft pick in the [[2007 Major League Baseball Draft|2007 MLB Draft]] out of [[Liberty-Eylau High School]] in [[Texarkana, Texas]], Middlebrooks signed with the Red Sox for $925,000, bypassing his commitment to [[Texas A&M University]]. Originally a [[shortstop]], the Red Sox converted Middlebrooks into a third baseman in the [[minor league baseball|minor leagues]]. He represented the United States in the 2011 [[All-Star Futures Game]]. Following Middlebrooks' emergence as the Red Sox' starting third baseman in 2012, the organization traded former [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] [[Kevin Youkilis]].

==Career==
===Amateur career===
Middlebrooks attended [[Liberty-Eylau High School]] in [[Texarkana, Texas]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/boston/access/2114972151.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Aug+20%2C+2010&author=Peter+Abraham&pub=Boston+Globe&desc=Middlebrooks+turning+the+corner+at+third+base&pqatl=google |title=Middlebrooks turning the corner at third base |newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]]|first=Peter|last=Abraham |date=August 20, 2010|accessdate=May 3, 2012}} {{subscription required|date=May 2012}}</ref> Middlebrooks played [[shortstop]] and [[pitcher|pitched]] for the high school baseball team. As a pitcher, he could reach {{convert|90|mph}} with his [[fastball]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=TXMB&p_theme=txmb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=117C59CDF145D888&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=Liberty-Eylau pitcher hits his way to a win|first=Jon Dustin |last=Brooks|date=March 9, 2007|newspaper=[[The Marshall News Messenger]]|accessdate=May 3, 2012}} {{subscription required|date=May 2012}}</ref> Liberty-Eylau won the Class 3A state championship in 2006, Middlebrooks' junior season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=LTJB&p_theme=ltjb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=111B6E3C8653FAD8&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=Carthage falls to L-E in playoff series opener|first=Joe|last=Hale|newspaper=Longview News-Journal |date=May 19, 2006 |accessdate=May 3, 2012}} {{subscription required|date=May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=AASB&p_theme=aasb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=119A35B9F708B6F0&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=Leopards get shot to defend state title|first=Rick |last=Cantu|date=June 7, 2007|newspaper=[[Austin American-Statesman]]|page=C06 |accessdate=May 3, 2012}} {{subscription required|date=May 2012}}</ref> In his senior season, Middlebrooks had a .555 [[batting average]].<ref name=kj>{{cite news|url=http://www.kjonline.com/sports/ON-BASEBALL-Middlebrooks-on-verge-of-breakout.html |title=Middlebrooks on verge of breakout |newspaper=[[Kennebec Journal]]|location=[[Augusta, Maine]] |date=May 30, 2011 |accessdate=August 8, 2012}}</ref> He was named to the Class 3A All-State First Team and Class 3A Player of the Year by the [[Texas Sports Writers Association]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=pqA_AAAAIBAJ&sjid=HFYMAAAAIBAJ&pg=1093,6022402&dq=will-middlebrooks&hl=en |title=High School Baseball: TSWA All-State Teams |newspaper=The Victoria Advocate |page=C2 |date=July 5, 2007 |accessdate=May 22, 2012}}</ref>

In addition to baseball, Middlebrooks played American football and basketball in high school.<ref name="on way"/> A [[quarterback]], [[placekicker]] and [[Punter (football)|punter]], he played on the school's football team, which also featured [[LaMichael James]].<ref name=mallett/><ref>{{cite news|first=Les |last=Giles|url=http://amarillo.com/stories/121006/hss_6279091.shtml |title=End of the line for Eagles: Liberty-Eylau hits Canyon defense with big plays in dominating victory|date=December 10, 2006|newspaper=[[Amarillo Globe-News]]|accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref> He was named an All-State punter.<ref name=mallett/> Middlebrooks admits that he preferred football, until he realized during his junior year that he had the opportunity to be selected in the [[Major League Baseball Draft]].<ref name="on way"/><ref name=football>{{cite web|url=http://www.nesn.com/2012/05/will-middlebrooks-played-high-school-football-with-lamichael-james-but-focus-has-been-on-baseball-ev.html |title=Will Middlebrooks Played High School Football With LaMichael James, But Focus Has Been on Baseball Ever Since|publisher=[[New England Sports Network]]|work=NESN.com|first=Ricky|last=Doyle|date=May 1, 2012 |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref> In November 2006, he committed to attend [[Texas A&M University]] on a full scholarship to play baseball and football for the [[Texas A&M Aggies]].<ref name=kj/><ref name="on way"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=LTJB&p_theme=ltjb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=117BE5671543A638&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=Hallsville, Marshall co-hosting tourney|first=Rick|last=Kretzschmar|newspaper=[[Longview News-Journal]]|date=March 8, 2007|accessdate=October 30, 2012}} {{subscription required|date=October 2012}}</ref>

===Professional career===
====Minor league baseball====
Middlebrooks had been projected as a first round talent in the [[2007 Major League Baseball Draft]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseballprospectus.com/article.php?articleid=7720|date=June 26, 2008|title=Future Shock: AL East|first=Kevin|last=Goldstein|work=Baseball Prospectus|accessdate=October 29, 2012}}</ref> However, the belief that he would follow through with his scholarship to Texas A&M led Middlebrooks to fall in the draft.<ref name=kj/> The [[Boston Red Sox]] drafted Middlebrooks in the fifth round of the draft, selecting him as a position player, rather than as a pitcher.<ref>{{cite web|first=Jonathan |last=Mayo|work=MiLB.com |url=http://www.milb.com/news/article.jsp?content_id=305486&fext=.jsp&vkey=news_milb&ymd=20070927 |title=Florida Instructional League Notebook: News & notes for the week of Sept. 24|publisher=Minor League Baseball|date=September 27, 2007 |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref> He received a $925,000 [[signing bonus]] to bypass his commitment to Texas A&M.<ref name=football/>

Middlebrooks made his professional debut in 2008 with the [[Lowell Spinners]] of the [[Class A-Short Season]] [[New York-Penn League]], where he batted .254 with one [[home run]]. He described himself as developmentally behind other players at his level because of the time he had devoted to football.<ref name="on way"/> Initially a [[shortstop]], Middlebrooks made the transition to [[third base]] as he added muscle, increasing from {{convert|190|lbs}} at the time he was drafted to {{convert|210|lbs}}.<ref name="on way"/>

[[File:Will Middlebrooks (7260091178).jpg|left|upright|thumb|Middlebrooks batting in May 2012]]
In 2009, Middlebrooks played for the [[Greenville Drive]] of the [[Class A (baseball)|Class A]] [[South Atlantic League]], where he batted. 265 with seven home runs and 57 [[runs batted in]] (RBIs).<ref name=milb>{{cite web|last=Driver |first=David |url=http://www.milb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20110815&content_id=23238806&fext=.jsp&vkey=news_milb |title=EL notes: Middlebrooks rolls along |publisher=Minor League Baseball|work=Milb.com |date=August 16, 2011 |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref> He was promoted to the [[Salem Red Sox]] of the [[Class A-Advanced]] [[Carolina League]] in 2010 and responded by batting .276 with 12 home runs and 70 RBIs.<ref name=milb/> Middlebrooks began the 2011 season playing for the [[Portland Sea Dogs]] of the Class AA [[Eastern League (baseball)|Eastern League]]. He played in the Eastern League All-Star Game, hitting a double in the game.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-194710197.html|newspaper=[[Portland Press Herald]]|date=July 14, 2011|first=Kevin|last=Thomas|title=Sea Dogs make impression; Will Middlebrooks and Alex Hassan hit doubles for the East, but the West emerges with an 8<U+2013>3 victory|accessdate=May 2, 2012}} {{subscription required|date=May 2012}}</ref> Middlebrooks also participated in the 2011 [[All-Star Futures Game]],<ref name=weei/> starting at third base and going 1-for-2.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.boston.com/2011-07-10/sports/29758688_1_middlebrooks-futures-globe-staff |title=Middlebrooks 1 for 2 in Futures Game|work=Boston.com |publisher=Boston Globe|date=July 10, 2011 |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref>

Through August 2011, Middlebrooks batted .306 with 18 home runs and 80 RBIs for Portland, at which point he was promoted to the [[Pawtucket Red Sox]] of the [[Class AAA]] [[International League]]. Joe McDonald of [[ESPN.com]] called Middlebrooks "Boston's likely [third baseman] of the future" upon his promotion from Portland to Pawtucket.<ref name="McDonald">{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/boston/mlb/story/_/id/6879360/will-middlebrooks-takes-giant-step-closer-fenway|title=A giant step closer to Fenway|last=McDonald|first=Joe|date=August 20, 2011|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|work=ESPN.com|accessdate=November 21, 2011}}</ref> He hit .161 in 16 games with Pawtucket to close out the 2011 season.<ref name="on way">{{cite web|first=John |last=Tomase|url=http://bostonherald.com/sports/baseball/red_sox/view.bg?articleid=1061127488&srvc=sports&position=3 |title=Will Middlebrooks on way: Bat, glove portend big future|publisher=BostonHerald.com |date=April 27, 2012|accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref>

After the 2011 season, the Red Sox assigned Middlebrooks to the [[Arizona Fall League]], where he hit four home runs in 13 games and was named to the Rising Stars Game.<ref name=mallett/><ref name=weei>{{cite web|last=Minihane |first=Kirk |url=http://fullcount.weei.com/sports/boston/baseball/red-sox/2011/11/01/red-sox-prospect-will-middlebrooks-named-to-arizona-fall-league-rising-stars-game/ |title=Full Count <U+00BB> Red Sox prospect Will Middlebrooks named to Arizona Fall League Rising Stars Game |publisher=[[WEEI]]|date=November 1, 2011 |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref> In November 2011, Middlebrooks, [[Che-Hsuan Lin]] and [[Drake Britton]] were added to the Red Sox 40-man roster to prevent them from being selected in the Rule 5 Draft.<ref name="Cole">{{cite web|url=http://www.nesn.com/2011/11/will-middlebrooks-che-hsuan-lin-drake-britton-added-to-red-sox-40-man-roster.html|title=Will Middlebrooks, Che-Hsuan Lin, Drake Britton Added to Red Sox' 40-Man Roster|last=Cole|first=Mike|date=November 19, 2011|publisher=New England Sports Network|work=NESN.com|accessdate=November 21, 2011}}</ref>

Heading into the 2012 season, ''[[Baseball America]]'' rated Middlebrooks as the Red Sox' best prospect and 51st best prospect overall.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pressherald.com/sports/ranaudo-may-be-hadlock-bound_2012-02-05.html |title=On Baseball: Ranaudo may be Hadlock-bound |work=[[The Portland Press Herald]]|publisher=MaineToday Media|first=Kevin |last=Thomas |date=February 5, 2012 |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref> Starting the 2012 season with Pawtucket, Middlebrooks hit .333 with nine home runs and 27 RBIs in 24 games and 93 [[at-bat]]s.<ref name=promote/> Meanwhile, Red Sox starting third baseman [[Kevin Youkilis]] struggled, opening the 2012 season batting .219.<ref name=promote/> As Youkilis struggled, Middlebrooks appeared to be ready for a promotion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boston.com/sports/baseball/redsox/extras/extra_bases/2012/04/as_youkilis_str.html|title=As Youkilis struggles, Middlebrooks impresses|first=Peter|last=Abraham|work=Boston.com|publisher=Boston Globe|date=April 18, 2012|accessdate=October 29, 2012}}</ref>

====Major League Baseball====
[[File:Kevin Youkilis , Will Middlebrooks (7253775924).jpg|right|upright|thumb|Middlebrooks congratulating [[Kevin Youkilis]]]]
The Red Sox promoted Middlebrooks to the major leagues on May 2, 2012, when Youkilis was placed on the [[disabled list]].<ref name=promote>{{cite web|url=http://boston.redsox.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20120502&content_id=30215554&vkey=news_bos&c_id=bos|title=Red Sox promote top prospect Middlebrooks|first=Ian|last=Browne|publisher=Major League Baseball Advanced Media|work=MLB.com|date=May 2, 2012|accessdate=May 2, 2012}}</ref> He made his MLB debut that day, drawing a [[base on balls|walk]] in his first plate appearance and recording two hits.<ref>{{cite web|first=Nick |last=Underhill |url=http://www.masslive.com/redsox/index.ssf/2012/05/will_middlebrooks_makes_strong.html |title=Will Middlebrooks makes strong debut in Red Sox' loss to A's |publisher=[[The Republican (Springfield)|The Republican]]|location=[[Springfield, Massachusetts]]|date=May 2, 2012 |accessdate=May 22, 2012}}</ref> On May 6, he hit a game-tying grand slam for his first major league home run in what was eventually a 17-inning loss to the [[Baltimore Orioles]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20120506&content_id=30549350&notebook_id=30611582&vkey=notebook_bos&c_id=bos |first=Ian |last=Browne |title=Middlebrooks' first MLB home run is grand |work=[[MLB.com]] |publisher=Major League Baseball Advanced Media |date=May 6, 2012 |accessdate=May 22, 2012}}</ref> In his first 41 games with the Red Sox, Middlebrooks batted .326 with nine home runs and 34 RBIs, the most RBIs to start a career for a member of the Red Sox since [[Walt Dropo]] recorded 37 RBIs in his first 41 career games dating back to 1949-50.<ref name=reins/>

[[Bobby Valentine]], the [[manager (baseball)|manager]] of the Red Sox, initially alternated between Middlebrooks and Youkilis at third base. However, Middlebrooks' emergence led the Red Sox to trade Youkilis on June 23.<ref name=reins>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20120624&content_id=33864132&vkey=news_mlb&c_id=mlb |first=Austin |last=Laymance|title=Hot Corner Heir: Middlebrooks handed reins |work=MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball Advanced Media |date=June 19, 2012|accessdate=June 26, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.providencejournal.com/sports/red-sox/2012/06/transition-complete-youkilis-traded-to-make-room-for-middlebrooks.html|title=Transition complete: Red Sox icon Youkilis traded to make room for rookie Middlebrooks|date=June 24, 2012|first=Brian|last=MacPherson|newspaper=[[The Providence Journal]]|accessdate=June 25, 2012}}</ref> Middlebrooks was named [[American League Player of the Week]] for the week ending June 24.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nesn.com/2012/06/will-middlebrooks-named-american-league-player-of-the-week.html |title=Middlebrooks Named AL Player of the week |first=Ricky|last=Doyle|publisher=New England Sports Network|work=NESN.com |date=June 25, 2012 |accessdate=June 26, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20120625&content_id=33900724&vkey=pr_mlb&c_id=mlb |title=Will Middlebrooks of the Boston Red Sox named the American League Player of the Week |work=MLB.com |publisher=Major League Baseball Advanced Media |date=June 25, 2012 |accessdate=August 8, 2012}}</ref> Middlebrooks broke a bone in his right hand when he was hit by a pitch in a game against the [[Cleveland Indians]] on August 10, ending his rookie season with a .288  batting average, 15 home runs and 54 RBIs in 75 games played.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://espn.go.com/boston/mlb/story/_/id/8259882/boston-red-sox-put-middlebrooks-dl-broken-wrist|title=Red Sox put Will Middlebrooks on DL|date=August 11, 2012|first=Bob|last=Finnan|work=ESPNBoston.com|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|accessdate=August 11, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://espn.go.com/boston/mlb/story/_/id/8367547/red-sox-3b-middlebrooks-gets-cast-wrist|title=Will Middlebrooks gets cast off|work=ESPNBoston.com|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|first=Joe|last=McDonald|date=September 11, 2012|accessdate=September 20, 2012}}</ref>

==Player profile==
Middlebrooks is an athletic defensive player. He hits for [[power hitter|power]]<ref name=ul/> and is also credited for his [[contact hitter|contact skills]],<ref name=milb/> though he is not considered the most patient hitter. His throwing arm is well regarded,<ref name=ul>{{cite web|url=http://www.unionleader.com/article/20110511/SPORTS0102/705119981|date=May 10. 2011|title=Kevin Gray's On Baseball: Sox prospect Middlebrooks on the attack|first=Kevin|last=Gray|publisher=New Hampshire Union Leader|accessdate=October 30, 2012}}</ref> and his baserunning is rated as average.<ref name=milb>{{cite web|url=http://www.milb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20111002&content_id=25445480&fext=.jsp&vkey=news_milb|title=Lavarnway, Brentz provide Sox with pop: Both sluggers top 30 homers, share Player of the Year honors|first=Ashley|last=Marshall|work=MiLB.com|publisher=Minor League Baseball|date=October 10, 2011|accessdate=October 30, 2012}}</ref>

==Personal==
Middlebrooks grew up in [[Texarkana, Texas]]. His father, Tom, serves as the head baseball coach and assistant American football coach at Liberty-Eylau, and his younger sister, Lacey, plays [[softball]] for the [[University of Tulsa]]. Middlebrooks' mother, Julie, and youngest sister, Mary, are artists; Julie is an art teacher.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/boston/mlb/story/_/id/7902591/middlebrooks-siblings-hit-simultaneous-homers|title=Middlebrooks lightning strikes twice: Red Sox third baseman Will, Tulsa softball player Lacey hit simultaneous home runs|date=May 8, 2012|first=Gordon|last=Edes|work=ESPNBoston.com|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|accessdate=August 8, 2012}}</ref> He has been friends with [[Ryan Mallett]] of the [[New England Patriots]] since they met in an American football camp after Mallet moved to the Texarkana area in the seventh grade.<ref name=mallett>{{cite web|url=http://www.boston.com/sports/baseball/redsox/extras/extra_bases/2012/02/mallett_and_mid.html |title=Mallett and Middlebrooks living the dream |newspaper=[[Boston Globe]] |publisher=The New York Times Company|date=February 1, 2012 |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bostonherald.com/blogs/sports/red_sox/index.php/2012/05/02/patriots-qb-ryan-mallett-anticipating-will-middlebrooks-mlb-debut/ |title=Patriots QB Ryan Mallett anticipating Will Middlebrooks<U+2019> MLB debut |publisher=Herald Media|work=BostonHerald.com |date=May 2, 2012 |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref>

Middlebrooks is engaged to Ann Lux, a former [[Dallas Cowboys cheerleader]].<ref name=football/><ref>{{cite web|last=Abraham|first=Peter|title=Will Middlebrooks making his case|url=http://www.boston.com/sports/baseball/redsox/extras/extra_bases/2012/04/middlebrooks_ma.html|work=Boston.com|publisher=Boston Globe|accessdate=May 4, 2012|date=April 24, 2012}}</ref> They are from the same hometown and have known each other since age 12.<ref name=lux>{{cite web|last=Lux|first=Ann|title=Farewell From Ann|url=http://www.dallascowboyscheerleaders.com/articles/behind-the-scenes/farewell-from-ann/|work=Dallas Cowboys Cheerleaders|accessdate=May 4, 2012|date=February 22, 2012}}</ref>
